[7] Argentina (Buenos Aires)
Date: Thu 29 Mar 2018 21:20 hs
Source: Radio Monte Carlo [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
http://www.radiomontecarlo.com.uy/articulos/articulos_masinfo.php?secc=articulos&id=45235&path=0.2292


The Ministry of Health of Buenos Aires confirmed that an 8-month-old baby contracted measles, which is the 1st case of the virus in Argentina in nearly 2 decades.

The baby does not have references or travel and was not previously vaccinated because she was not 12-months old yet, so it is the 1st indigenous case of this disease, and warnings about its spread worry the government of the capital.

It was not until last [Sun 18 Mar 2018] when the girl began presenting eruptions, reddish skin, and was not hospitalized until [Mon 19 Mar 2018]. She previously only had minor symptoms such as cough and fever, which did not worry her parents.

In Argentina, an indigenous case of measles has not been diagnosed since 2000, so this episode is a warning for the entire health system.

Doctors warned that we must be alert to symptoms - fever, cough, skin blemishes, rashes and conjunctivitis - manifested 2 days after contracting the virus.

Only this case is known and work is being done "to identify the source of the contagion "and to check that there are no more diagnosed cases.

[Byline: Joaquin Deleon]

